items.name: Coffee
description: Brewed beverage made from roasted coffee beans.
Can be prepared under high pressure and higher concentrations to produce espresso, increasing caffeine content per unit volume.
Generally contains around 100mg of caffeine per cup, but can have as much as 200 mg in larger sizes.
items.credit: Photo by Nathan Dumlao on Unsplash

items.name: Caffeine
description: Not regarded as harmful in recommended doses, could potentially be of benefit in moderation.
Levels peak in 15 - 45 minutes.
Increases alertness, relieves tiredness, improves though processes, and enhances physical performance.
Constricts blood vessels often resulting in headache relief.
Central nervous system stimulant/psychoactive.
Often used in over the counter headache relief medicines.

items.name: Shampoo
description: Hair care product used to clean hair of sebum.
Normally manufactured using a mixture of a surfactant (a chemical separator), a co-surfactant, water, and fragrance.
items.credit: Photo by Jonny Caspari on Unsplash

items.name: Dry Shampoo
description: Aerosol shampoo product that reduces hair grease.
Produced from corn/rice starch.
Not recommended for long term use.

items.name: Dandruff Shampoo
description: Regular shampoo containing fungicides or various essential oils to reduce dandruff, such as tea-tree

items.name: Baby Shampoo
description: Diluted shampoo with a neutral pH.
Less irritating due to non-ionic surfactants used in manufacture

items.name: Toothpaste
description: Solid cleaning agent that assists in scrubbing off dental plaque and suppressing halitosis.
Consists of an abrasive, a detergent, fluoride, anti-dry agents, and flavoring.
Fluoride assists in preventing dental decalcification, but is toxic if swallowed.
Whitening toothpastes usually contain peroxide, which can allegedly permanently reduce enamel composition.

items.name: Mouthwash
description: Mouth rinsing agent intended to reduce microbes in hard to reach oral cavities.
Alcohol mouthwashes can cause a later dryness in mouth, causing halitosis.

items.name: Whitestrips
description: Plastic strips coated with a layer of peroxide gel, a bleaching agent.

items.name: Soy candles
description: Candles made from soy wax.
Soy wax is manufactured by hydrogenation of soybean oil, yielding triglycerides.
Normally softer than paraffin wax, with a lower melting temperature

items.name: Paraffin candles
description: Candles made from paraffin wax.
Paraffin wax is manufactured from oil industry byproducts, and is also used in industrial lubrication and electrical insulation.
When burned, paraffin wax burns off benzene and toluene in to the air (both are known carcinogens).

items.name: High-fructose corn syrup
description: Liquid glucose and fructose syrup derived from corn starch.
Produced via specialized enzymes and manufacture process introduced in the 60s.
Easier to handle than sugar. FDA generally regards as safe, however isolated dietary fructose has been associated with numerous health issues.
HFCS 42 – 42% fructose (used in processed foods). HFCS 55 – 55% fructose (used in beverages).

items.name: Molasses
description: Syrup product derived from refined sugarcane, popularized in the 20th century.
Mainly a mixture of glucose and fructose, with small amounts of maltose and sucrose.
Blackstrap molasses contain high amounts of vitamin B6, calcium, potassium, and other minerals.
Unsulphured molasses do not undergo the outdated technique of bleaching/preserving molasses with Sulphur dioxide.

items.name: Honey
description: Sweet syrup produced by honeybees (and other various insects).
Microorganisms can not thrive in the viscous environment, therefore it does not have a defined shelf-life.
Can have negative effects in infants, individuals taking medications, or that have preexisting conditions.
Bees will transport the nectar from thousands of plants over an hour or so, and digest it with salivary enzymes.
They store this honey in the hive for an energy source for later foraging.

items.name: Maple syrup
description: Sweet syrup produced from sap of various maple trees.
In cold climates, the maple trees will store excess sugar carbohydrates in their trunk before winter as sap.
Mainly consists of sucrose, with a small raw glucose/fructose content. Low in nutrition, except for a high manganese content.
Real maple syrup costs about $40-60/gal to produce, while imitation maple-flavored syrup can cost as low as $8/gal.

items.name: Sugar (refined, granulated)
description: Isolated crystals of sucrose, refined.
Found in most plants, especially in sugarcane and sugarbeet.

Most sugar used is refined by a stepwise process which includes softening and removing the brown layer, dissolving then carbonation in water, then the sugar precipitates out and is isolated via centrifuge.
Some brands use bone char in the refining process, so some consider these not be vegan.

items.name: Sugar (refined, powdered)
description: Finely milled sugar with small amounts of anti-caking additives.
Available in various levels of fineness (higher number of X's = more fine).
Caster sugar is similar but is slightly larger than powdered, and smaller than granulated.

items.name: Erythritol
description: Sugar alcohol produced from yeast fermentation of glucose.
60-70% as sweet as sucrose but does not affect blood sugar levels, cause tooth decay, and is mostly untouched by the body during digestion.
Excreted mainly through kidneys.
Great alternative to sugar in most recipes, but due to its inability to carmelize it should be avoided in baking.

items.name: Xylitol
description: Naturally occurring sugar alcohol, used as a sugar replacement in food manufacture.
Produced industrially via hydrolyzation of biomass.
Used as an additive in chewing gum, toothpaste, and other various supplements.
Toxic to animals.

items.name: Baking soda
description: Baking/leavening agent made of sodium bicarbonate.
Reacts with acid in baking mixture to form carbon dioxide gas, which leads to the signature rise (or by heat decomposition-which results in a soapy tasting bake).
Acids used to react with baking soda include cream of tartar, buttermilk, or lemon juice.
Has strong odor fighting abilities, can be used for teeth whitening, and even calming indegestion.

items.name: Baking powder
description: Dry chemical leavening agent made of a mixture of carbonate/bicarbonate and a weak acid.
Used to increase volume in baking mixtures instead of yeast where an fermentation taste would be undesirable.

items.name: Xanthan gum
description: Thickening agent/stabilizer used in food manufacture.
Used to stabilize oil emulsions (such as dressings, marinade) and suspend solid particles (herbs, spices).
Used in ice-creams to create texture, and also as a binding agent in toothpaste.
Used in gluten free baking to achieve desired stickiness that gluten brings.
Also used in oil and cosmetic industry for various applications.

items.name: Flour (wheat)
description: Powder made from grinding wheat, typically contain varying levels of gluten forming proteins.
White flour generally only uses the endosperm in processing, the middle/soft part of the grain, while whole-grain flour uses the entire grain: bran, endosperm, and germ.
Typically contain two proteins: glutenin and gliadin; which in the prescence of water become hydrated and form chemical cross-links; thus merging together to form gluten.
Gluten gives bread the characteristic elasticity and toughness that holds its shape.

items.name: Soap
description: General name for cleaning agents made by reacting alkali (base) with various fats.
Assist water in dissolving non-aqueous, oily surfaces by acting as a surfactant.
Soaps are produced from natural products. Detergents are synthetic.
They essentially break the surface tension of water to make water 'wetter'—more effective at breaking up oily dirt.

Both contain long chain fatty acids with a hydrophobic region that dissolves oil particles, and a hydrophilic end that dissolves in the water; pulling the oil and dirt off and dissolving in the water.

items.name: Bubble bath
description: Regular soap with added foaming surfactants that are aerated by the falling water to produce a foam bath.

items.name: Neem oil
description: Oil pressed from the fruits/seeds of neem trees.
Varies in color, with a strong peanut/chemical odor.
Consists of triglycerides and triterpenoid compounds, giving it a bitter taste. Hydrophobic on its own, surfactants are usually added to increase water solvation.
Not used in the kitchen, has wide applications in gardening and cosmetics.
Highly toxic if ingested, associated with liver damage in children.
Pesticide.

items.name: Lemon juice
description: Juice from a lemon fruit.
Can be used in cooking to add acidity, can clean glass/mirrors, disinfecting agent, brighten white surfaces.
Also a detox agent, strengthens immunity, and can sooth a sore throat.

items.name: Vinegar (white distilled)
description: Acetic acid, diluted with water.
Multipurpose product, produced by fermentation of just about anything that contains carbohydrates.
Can be used to polish silver, clean windows, neutralize odors, unclog drains.
Can also tenderize meat, cure an upset stomach, and even condition your hair.

items.name: Vinegar (apple cider)
description: Vinegar made from fermented apple juice.
Repels fleas, cleaning agent, deodorizing agent.
Assists in detox, blood pressure control, cold prevention.
Usually diluted, as drinking large amounts can be harmful.

items.name: Coconut oil
description: Oil extracted from the kernel/meat of a coconut from the coconut palm.
Relatively high in saturated fat, with a moderately low smoke point.
Extracted through wet or dry processing, can also be hydrogenated or fractionated.
Lasts long without spoiling due to slow rate of oxidation. 99% fat – mainly saturated fats such as Lauric acid.
Hydrogenated coconut oils are often used in processed food, and non-dairy coffee creamers. Smoke point: 175C/347F.

items.name: Butter
description: Dairy product high in butterfat (80%+), solid at room temperature.
Produced by churning fresh or fermented cream/milk in order to separate the butterfat from the buttermilk.

Contains trace amounts of lactose, therefore small amounts okay for individuals with lactose intolerance; not recommended for people with milk allergies (contains allergy-causing proteins other than lactose).
Relatively high amounts of saturated fats, with small amounts of Vitamin A.

items.name: Vitamin A
description: Group of fat soluble, nutritional organic compounds that plays roles in: vision, gene transcription, embryonic development, bone metabolism, skin, teeth, mucuous membrane strength, immune function
Found in retinol (animal food sources) as retinyl acetate or palmitate; or from carotenes and xanthophyll in plants.
Vitamin A deficiency can result in blindness (leading cause of childhood blindness).
Increases risk of death from common childhood conditions, such as diarrhea.
First symptoms include impaired vision, particularly in reduced light/night blindness.

items.name: Quinine
description: Alkaloid commonly used as an antimalarial drug (mechanism not well understood), also used as a mild antipyretic, analgesic, and for fighting colds.
Also used as a bitter in flavoring agent.

items.name: Gelatin
description: Food ingredient manufactured from various animal tissue that is high in collagen.
It is a flavorless and colorless substance, and provides the texture found in marshmallows, gummies, and other various food products.

items.name: Apple butter
description: Similar to apple sauce, but involves a slow carmelization process during manufacture.
This results in a highly concentrated form of apple sauce.

items.name: Aquafaba
description: Name referring to the liquid used to cook beans/legumes, present in most cans of beans (notably chickpeas).
Highly praised as an egg white replacement due to its unique composition of starches, proteins, and other plant solids.

items.name: Linseed oil
description: Also known as flaxseed oil.
